<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{ppanashi}}}} is an auxiliary that expresses the idea that someone or something keeps doing something or that something is left in an improper state.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{friend^accomplished}}nimadao@KJ{{gold}}wo@KJ{{borrow}}ri@EM{{ppanashi}}da.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I borrowed money from a friend and I still haven't paid it back.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{ppanashi}}}} is derived from the @HI{{masu}} stem of @HI{{hanasu}}, "to leave".
</p>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{ppanashi}}}} when attached to an intransitive verb means that someone or something keeps performing an action.
When attached to a transitive verb it means that someone does something to X and leaves it in that state, which is not the proper way.
</p>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{ppanashi}}}} behaves as a noun.
</p>

